    s_brain: `<div class="rich-h1">What Is Happening in the Brain</div>
<p class="rich-p">The part of the brain most affected in ADHD is the prefrontal cortex — the area behind your forehead that handles planning, organising, attention, impulse control, and emotional regulation. In ADHD, this system is less active than it should be.</p>
<p class="rich-p">The two main chemical messengers involved are dopamine and noradrenaline. Dopamine helps drive motivation and filter out distractions. Noradrenaline sharpens focus on what matters. In ADHD, both are in short supply in the circuits that run the prefrontal cortex.</p>
<p class="rich-p">A simple way to picture it: imagine trying to listen to someone talk in a room where all the background noise is just as loud as their voice. That is what paying attention feels like in ADHD — not a lack of effort, but a brain that is struggling to filter what is important from what is not.</p>
<p class="rich-p">One key feature is that the ADHD brain is interest-driven rather than priority-driven. When something is new, urgent, or genuinely interesting, the brain activates well. When something is important but boring, it does not. That is why someone with ADHD can spend hours hyperfocusing on something they enjoy, then struggle to start a five-minute task they have been putting off. It is not a choice. It is how the reward system is wired.</p>`,

    s_core: `<div class="rich-h1">Core Symptoms</div>
