<p class="rich-p">Dexamphetamine is a stimulant that acts on the dopamine and noradrenaline systems in the prefrontal cortex. It blocks the transporter proteins that normally clear these signals, directly triggers dopamine release from inside neurons, and reverses the transporter — actively pumping dopamine into the synapse. This triple mechanism produces a larger increase in dopamine and noradrenaline than methylphenidate-based medications, which is why head-to-head studies show a somewhat larger effect size.</p>
