  <li><strong>Important interaction:</strong> Avoid with fluoxetine (Prozac), paroxetine (Aropax), or bupropion — these can dramatically increase atomoxetine blood levels and side effects.</li>
</ul>
<div class="rich-h2">What to Expect</div>
<p class="rich-p">Strattera improves attention, impulse control, and emotional regulation, but the onset is slow. Initial side effects (nausea, fatigue) often settle within the first few weeks. It is a good option for people with anxiety, tic disorders, or a history of substance use, or as an add-on to stimulants.</p>`,

    s_meds_intuniv: `<div class="rich-h1">Medication: Intuniv</div>
<div class="rich-h2">How It Works</div>
<p class="rich-p">Intuniv (guanfacine extended-release) is a non-stimulant that works on alpha-2A adrenergic receptors in the prefrontal cortex. Activating these receptors strengthens the connections between prefrontal neurons that control attention and impulse regulation — essentially improving the signal quality in circuits that ADHD disrupts. It does not affect dopamine directly and has no abuse potential.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Practical Details</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Dosing:</strong> Once daily, titrated slowly upward over weeks.</li>
  <li><strong>Onset:</strong> Gradual — therapeutic effect develops over 4-8 weeks of dose titration.</li>
  <li><strong>Do not stop suddenly:</strong> Stopping guanfacine abruptly can cause rebound hypertension and tachycardia. Always taper the dose under medical guidance.</li>
  <li><strong>Timing:</strong> Take at the same time each day. Avoid high-fat meals as they increase absorption and can increase side effects.</li>
</ul>
<div class="rich-h2">What to Expect</div>
<p class="rich-p">Guanfacine is particularly helpful for emotional dysregulation, impulsivity, and hyperactivity. It is often used in combination with stimulants. Sedation is the most common side effect, especially in the first few weeks — this usually settles. Low blood pressure and slow heart rate are also common.</p>`,

    s_meds_catapres: `<div class="rich-h1">Medication: Catapres</div>
<div class="rich-h2">How It Works</div>
<p class="rich-p">Catapres (clonidine) is a non-stimulant that acts on alpha-2 adrenergic receptors in the brain and peripheral nervous system. In ADHD, it helps regulate arousal, reduce impulsivity, and improve sleep-onset — the latter makes it particularly useful when taken in the evening. Like guanfacine, it has no abuse potential, but it has a broader pharmacological profile and requires careful management.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Practical Details</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Dosing:</strong> Titrated slowly. Your psychiatrist will specify your exact dose and schedule.</li>
  <li><strong>Do not stop suddenly:</strong> Stopping clonidine abruptly can cause a rebound rise in blood pressure and heart rate. Always taper the dose under medical guidance.</li>
  <li><strong>Alcohol:</strong> Significantly increases sedation. Avoid or strictly limit alcohol while taking clonidine.</li>
  <li><strong>Blood pressure medications:</strong> Effects can add up — let all your doctors know you are taking clonidine.</li>
</ul>
<div class="rich-h2">What to Expect</div>
<p class="rich-p">Clonidine is useful for managing hyperarousal, impulsivity, and sleep difficulties associated with ADHD. Sedation is common, especially at first. Low blood pressure and dizziness (particularly on standing) are also common. These effects often diminish after the first few weeks at a stable dose.</p>`,

    s_monitor: `<div class="rich-h1">What to Monitor During Titration</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Positive Effects to Track</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Focus and concentration — is it easier to start and stay on tasks?</li>
  <li>Internal restlessness — is the background agitation quieter?</li>
  <li>Impulse control — more pause before reacting?</li>
  <li>Mood and anxiety — is the baseline anxiety lower?</li>
  <li>Energy and motivation — easier to get going?</li>
  <li>Productivity — completing more of what you intend to each day?</li>
</ul>
<div class="rich-h2">Side Effects to Track</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Appetite — eating less, losing weight?</li>
  <li>Sleep — harder to fall asleep or waking earlier?</li>
  <li>Heart rate / chest — any palpitations or chest discomfort?</li>
  <li>Blood pressure — check regularly if any cardiovascular history</li>
  <li>Mood — any increase in anxiety, irritability, or flatness?</li>
  <li>Headaches or nausea — particularly in first two weeks</li>
  <li>Rebound — mood crash in late afternoon or evening?</li>
</ul>
<div class="rich-h2">When to Pause Titration</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li class="rich-warn">Heart rate persistently above 100 bpm at rest, or chest pain, palpitations, or shortness of breath</li>
  <li class="rich-warn">Blood pressure consistently elevated above 140/90</li>
  <li class="rich-warn">Significant increase in anxiety or panic that is not settling</li>
  <li class="rich-warn">New or worsening psychotic symptoms — unusual thoughts, paranoia, perceptual disturbances</li>
  <li class="rich-warn">Marked mood elevation, unusually high energy, or reduced need for sleep</li>
  <li class="rich-warn">Significant insomnia not resolved by adjusting timing</li>
  <li class="rich-warn">Severe appetite suppression with noticeable weight loss</li>
  <li class="rich-warn">Emotional blunting at the current dose — reduce dose, do not increase</li>
</ul>`,

    s_safety: `<div class="rich-h1">Important Safety Considerations</div>
<div class="rich-h2">When to Stop and Seek Urgent Help</div>
<p class="rich-p rich-warn">Stop the medication and contact your doctor or emergency services immediately if you experience chest pain, irregular heartbeat, signs of hypertensive crisis (severe headache, visual changes, confusion), or any psychotic symptoms.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Cannabis</div>
<p class="rich-p">Cannabis and stimulant medications are a genuinely poor combination. Cannabis impairs working memory, attentional control, and executive function — the exact same systems ADHD medication is trying to support. Regular cannabis use significantly reduces treatment effectiveness and can worsen ADHD symptoms. There is also increased cardiovascular stress with the combination.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Alcohol</div>
<p class="rich-p">Stimulants can mask the sedating effects of alcohol, increasing the risk of drinking significantly more than intended. There is also increased cardiovascular load. Warrants awareness and restraint.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Drug Interactions</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong class="rich-warn">MAOIs: absolute contraindication.</strong> Do not combine under any circumstances.</li>
  <li><strong>Other stimulants / sympathomimetics:</strong> combining with other stimulant drugs significantly increases cardiovascular risk.</li>
  <li><strong>Decongestants (pseudoephedrine):</strong> avoid combining without medical advice.</li>
  <li><strong>Antidepressants:</strong> most SSRIs and SNRIs are compatible. Do not add or change other medications without disclosing to your psychiatrist.</li>
</ul>
<div class="rich-h2">Do Not Share Your Medication</div>
<p class="rich-p">Stimulant medications are controlled substances in Australia. Sharing them is illegal, places the recipient at risk, and can affect your ability to continue receiving treatment.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Pregnancy and Breastfeeding</div>
<p class="rich-p">If you are pregnant, planning to become pregnant, or breastfeeding, speak with your psychiatrist before starting or continuing stimulant medication.</p>`,

    s_myths: `<div class="rich-h1">Common Myths About ADHD</div>
<div class="rich-h2">"Stimulants are addictive"</div>
<p class="rich-p">This is probably the most common concern people have, and the evidence does not support it. Prescribed stimulant medication taken orally at therapeutic doses does not cause addiction. In fact, research consistently shows that treating ADHD with medication <em>reduces</em> the risk of developing substance use problems, not the other way around.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">"If the medication works, that proves you have ADHD"</div>
<p class="rich-p">Not quite. Stimulants increase dopamine in everyone's brain. The difference is that without ADHD, you tend to just get side effects — increased heart rate, anxiety, reduced appetite — without much cognitive benefit. The medication response is useful information, but it is not a diagnostic test on its own.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">"ADHD medication stunts growth in children"</div>
<p class="rich-p">Stimulants can slightly reduce appetite, which may slow growth rate temporarily in some children. There is no convincing evidence that they affect final adult height. This is something that gets monitored, but it is not a reason to avoid treatment when it is needed.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">"Everyone feels like this — it's just normal"</div>
<p class="rich-p">Everyone gets distracted sometimes. ADHD is not about occasional inattention. It is about a consistent, pervasive pattern of impairment that has been present since childhood and affects multiple areas of life — work, relationships, daily functioning. The brain differences in ADHD are measurable on neuroimaging. It is a real, well-documented condition.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">"ADHD only affects children"</div>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD continues into adulthood in around 60% of cases. In adults it often looks different — less obvious hyperactivity, more internal restlessness, chronic underperformance, and difficulty with organisation and follow-through. Many adults are only diagnosed after years of wondering why things feel so much harder for them than for others.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">"People with ADHD just need to try harder"</div>
<p class="rich-p">People with ADHD are often trying extremely hard already. The problem is not effort — it is a brain that does not regulate attention and motivation the same way other brains do. Telling someone with ADHD to try harder is like telling someone with poor eyesight to look harder. The answer is the right tool, not more willpower.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">"ADHD is overdiagnosed / made up"</div>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD is one of the most researched psychiatric conditions in existence. It has consistent genetic findings, reproducible neuroimaging differences, and decades of clinical trial data. Whether it is overdiagnosed in some contexts is a fair debate. Whether it exists is not.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">"You can't have ADHD if you can focus on things you enjoy"</div>
<p class="rich-p">This is a very common misconception. The ADHD brain does not have a focus problem across the board — it has a <em>regulation</em> problem. When something is interesting, novel, or urgent, the brain can hyperfocus intensely. When something is dull or feels low-stakes, focus evaporates. That inconsistency is part of what makes ADHD confusing and why it goes unrecognised for so long.</p>`,

    s_faq: `<div class="rich-h1">Commonly Asked Questions</div>
<div class="rich-h2">How quickly will I notice a difference?</div>
<p class="rich-p">With stimulants, you usually notice an effect on the same day — sometimes on the very first dose. That is one of the distinguishing features of ADHD pharmacotherapy. That said, finding the right dose and formulation takes time. The first dose tells you the medication is working, not that you have found the optimal dose yet.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Do I have to take it every day?</div>
<p class="rich-p">Generally, yes — the recommendation is to take your medication every day. ADHD does not take weekends off, and consistency helps with titration and makes it easier to track how the medication is working. That said, some people choose to reduce or skip stimulants on weekends or during periods of intense physical exercise. This is an individual decision to discuss with your psychiatrist.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Will I need to take it forever?</div>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD is a lifelong condition for most people, so the need for support tends to persist. That said, some people find their need changes as circumstances and coping strategies evolve. We review this periodically. It is a tool you use when it is useful.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Will it change my personality?</div>
<p class="rich-p">No. Stimulants at therapeutic doses should make you feel more like yourself — more able to follow through on what you actually want to do. If it makes you feel flat or robotic, the dose is probably too high. That is a signal to adjust.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Is it safe long-term?</div>
<p class="rich-p">Yes, with monitoring. Stimulants have been used clinically since the 1930s. The main considerations are cardiovascular — blood pressure and heart rate — which we monitor regularly. The risk-benefit balance is almost always strongly in favour of treatment.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Can I drink alcohol on it?</div>
<p class="rich-p">It is not a great combination. Stimulants can mask the sedating effects of alcohol, increasing the risk of drinking more than intended. Warrants awareness.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">What if it does not work or I cannot tolerate it?</div>
<p class="rich-p">If one stimulant class does not work, we try the other. If stimulants are not tolerated or not suitable, non-stimulant options — atomoxetine and guanfacine — are effective alternatives for the right patient.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Can I drive while on it?</div>
<p class="rich-p">Yes. Medication does not restrict you from driving. The evidence actually shows lower crash rates in people with ADHD when they are on medication compared to when they are not. There are no specific restrictions on driving in Australia for people taking ADHD medications as prescribed.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">What happens if I miss a dose?</div>
<p class="rich-p">Take it as soon as you remember, provided it is not too late in the day. If it is past early afternoon, skip the missed dose and continue normally the next morning. Do not double up.</p>`,

