    s_supports: `<div class="rich-h1">Accessing Supports &amp; Services</div>
<p class="rich-p">Being diagnosed with ADHD opens up access to supports and services that may not have been available to you before. These are not charity — they are structured, evidence-based resources designed for people in exactly your situation.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">NDIS (National Disability Insurance Scheme)</div>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD may qualify you for NDIS funding, particularly if the condition causes significant functional impairment in daily life, work, or self-care. The key is demonstrating functional impact — not just having the diagnosis. A psychologist or occupational therapist (OT) can assist with a functional assessment if you choose to apply. An OT can also help implement practical supports at home and work. NDIS supports that may be relevant include:</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Capacity building for daily living and self-management</li>
  <li>Support coordination</li>
  <li>Assistive technology (apps, tools, organisational aids)</li>
  <li>Therapeutic supports (psychology, OT)</li>
</ul>
<p class="rich-p">Note: ADHD alone does not guarantee NDIS approval. The focus is on functional impairment, not diagnosis. A strong application includes detailed evidence of how symptoms impact daily activities.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Medicare-Funded Psychology</div>
<p class="rich-p">Under a Mental Health Treatment Plan from your GP, you can access up to 10 individual psychology sessions per calendar year at a Medicare rebate. This can be used for ADHD-focused Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT), skills coaching, or support for comorbid anxiety or depression. Ask your GP to refer you to a psychologist with ADHD experience.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Disability Support at Work or Study</div>
<p class="rich-p">If you are in employment or tertiary education, you have the right to request reasonable adjustments. At university and TAFE, disability services can provide extended time for exams, assignment extensions, and alternative assessment formats. In the workplace, reasonable adjustments are covered under the Disability Discrimination Act 1992 — your employer cannot legally discriminate based on a disability that is being appropriately managed. You do not have to disclose your specific diagnosis — you can request adjustments based on your functional needs.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">Peer Support and Community</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>ADHD Australia:</strong> <a href="https://www.adhdaustralia.org.au" target="_blank">adhdaustralia.org.au</a> — peer support groups, webinars, and community forums</li>
  <li><strong>ADHD Support Australia:</strong> online community and resources for adults and families</li>
  <li><strong>Beyond Blue:</strong> for comorbid anxiety and depression support — <a href="https://www.beyondblue.org.au" target="_blank">beyondblue.org.au</a></li>
</ul>`,

    s_workplace: `<div class="rich-h1">Workplace Adjustments</div>
<p class="rich-p">Most people with ADHD are highly capable — they often have creativity, drive, and the ability to hyperfocus on what they find engaging. The challenge is that standard workplace environments are often poorly matched to how ADHD brains work best. The good news is that targeted adjustments can make a significant difference.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">What You Can Request</div>
<p class="rich-p">Under Australian workplace law (Disability Discrimination Act 1992 and Fair Work Act 2009), employers are required to make reasonable adjustments for employees with disabilities, including ADHD, as long as these do not cause unjustifiable hardship. You are not required to disclose your diagnosis — you can frame requests around functional needs.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Flexible hours:</strong> ADHD brains often function better at particular times of day. If possible, aligning demanding work to your peak medication window (typically mid-morning) helps significantly.</li>
  <li><strong>Reduced interruptions:</strong> access to a quieter space, noise-cancelling headphones, or permission to use focus-only periods (e.g., no meetings before 10am)</li>
  <li><strong>Written instructions:</strong> requesting that key information, deadlines, and task changes be provided in writing rather than verbally</li>
  <li><strong>Task chunking:</strong> breaking large projects into structured milestones with check-ins, rather than open-ended deadlines</li>
  <li><strong>Extended time:</strong> for some roles and tasks, a slightly longer runway for completion improves quality without affecting output</li>
  <li><strong>Remote or hybrid work:</strong> many people with ADHD work more efficiently in a controlled home environment with fewer social interruptions</li>
</ul>
<div class="rich-h2">Communicating With Your Manager</div>
<p class="rich-p">You are not obliged to disclose your ADHD diagnosis. Many people find it effective to frame requests around performance optimisation rather than disability: "I do my best work when I have a block of uninterrupted time in the morning" is often better received than a formal disability disclosure, and is equally true. That said, formal disclosure may be appropriate if you need documented adjustments or if your performance has been formally managed — an HR conversation with appropriate documentation provides legal protection.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">If You Are Self-Employed or Freelance</div>
<p class="rich-p">Being your own boss removes some barriers but introduces others (no external accountability structure, inconsistent income triggers anxiety, admin tasks are painful). Practical strategies that work well for ADHD self-employed individuals:</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Set recurring calendar blocks for admin, invoicing, and correspondence</li>
  <li>Use project management tools with notifications (Trello, Notion, Asana) rather than relying on memory</li>
  <li>Body doubling — working alongside another person (even via video call) increases task initiation significantly</li>
  <li>Consider an accountability partner or business coach familiar with ADHD</li>
</ul>`,

