    s_grief: `<div class="rich-h1">Grief After Late Diagnosis</div>
<p class="rich-p">For many people diagnosed with ADHD as an adult, relief is the first thing they feel — finally an explanation for a lifetime of experiences that never quite made sense. But relief is often followed by something harder to name: grief.</p>
<p class="rich-p">Grief for the years spent struggling harder than you needed to. For the jobs that did not work out, the relationships that frayed under the strain, the exams you failed despite studying, the mornings you could not get started and blamed yourself for it. For the version of yourself that might have emerged earlier, with the right support.</p>
<p class="rich-p">This is a real and legitimate grief. It deserves to be acknowledged, not bypassed. You were not lazy, disorganised, or difficult. You were managing a neurological condition without a diagnosis, without tools, and often without understanding from the people around you. That is genuinely hard, and it accumulated over years.</p>
<p class="rich-p">It can also be disorienting to improve. When things start working — when the medication helps and you can actually follow through — there is sometimes a strange mourning that surfaces. "Why couldn't I do this before? What was all of that for?" These are not signs that something is wrong. They are the natural emotional processing of a significant life narrative shift.</p>
<p class="rich-p">Some things worth sitting with:</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>The diagnosis does not rewrite the past — but it does change the meaning of it. The failures were not character failures. They were the predictable outcomes of an unmanaged condition in environments that weren't built for you.</li>
  <li>Anger is appropriate, and it belongs somewhere. At the systems that missed you, perhaps. At outdated ideas about what ADHD looks like. Not at yourself.</li>
  <li>The future is not the same as the past. Having a diagnosis and a treatment plan genuinely changes the trajectory.</li>
</ul>
<p class="rich-p">If this grief feels heavy or persistent, talking to a psychologist — particularly one with experience in ADHD and identity — can be very worthwhile. This is not a detour from treatment; it is part of it.</p>`,

