    s_nonpharm_cbt: `<div class="rich-h1">Non-Pharmacological Therapies</div>
<p class="rich-p">Medication is the most effective single treatment for ADHD, but non-pharmacological approaches are an important part of comprehensive care. The strongest evidence is for approaches that directly train or scaffold executive function skills. These are not alternatives to medication — they work best alongside it.</p>
<div class="rich-h2">1. Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT) for ADHD</div>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Evidence: Strong. Highest level of evidence for psychological intervention in adult ADHD.</strong></p>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD-focused CBT is distinct from general CBT. It targets the functional impairments of ADHD directly: time management, organisation, procrastination, emotional regulation, and the negative self-beliefs that accumulate after years of underperformance. It does not try to treat inattention directly — it builds compensatory strategies around it.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Safren et al. (2005, 2010) demonstrated significant symptom and functional improvement in two RCTs of adults with ADHD on medication using ADHD-specific CBT, compared to medication alone. Effects were maintained at 12-month follow-up.<br><span class="rich-cite">Safren SA et al. J Consult Clin Psychol. 2010;78(4):491.</span></li>
  <li>A Cochrane review found CBT for adult ADHD produced significant improvement in ADHD symptoms, depression, anxiety, and quality of life compared to control conditions.<br><span class="rich-cite">Lopez PL et al. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2018.</span></li>
  <li>Sessions typically focus on: building planning and scheduling systems, breaking tasks into steps, managing procrastination cycles, reducing avoidance, and challenging all-or-nothing thinking about performance.</li>
</ul>
<p class="rich-p">Look for a psychologist with specific ADHD experience. General CBT without ADHD adaptation is less effective for this population.</p>`,

    s_nonpharm_coaching: `<div class="rich-h1">Non-Pharmacological Therapies</div>
<div class="rich-h2">ADHD Coaching</div>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Evidence: Moderate. Growing evidence base for goal attainment, executive function, and quality of life outcomes.</strong></p>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD coaching is not therapy — it is skills-focused, present-oriented, and highly practical. A coach works with you on specific goals: building routines, managing time, completing projects, improving follow-through. Unlike therapy, it does not address underlying psychological patterns. It is best suited to people who are functionally stable but need structured accountability and skills scaffolding.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Kubik (2010) found coached adults showed significant improvement in ADHD symptoms and quality of life measures compared to waitlist controls.<br><span class="rich-cite">Kubik JA. J Atten Disord. 2010;13(5):515.</span></li>
  <li>A systematic review found coaching produced meaningful improvements in time management, organisation, and goal attainment in adults with ADHD, though study quality is variable.<br><span class="rich-cite">Ahmann E et al. J Atten Disord. 2018;22(1):3.</span></li>
</ul>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD Australia (adhdaustralia.org.au) maintains a directory of coaches. Look for coaches certified through the ICF (International Coaching Federation) with ADHD-specific training.</p>`,

    s_nonpharm_mindful: `<div class="rich-h1">Non-Pharmacological Therapies</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Mindfulness-Based Interventions</div>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Evidence: Moderate. Particularly effective for emotional dysregulation and attentional control.</strong></p>
<p class="rich-p">Mindfulness training improves meta-cognitive awareness — the ability to notice when attention has wandered and redirect it. For ADHD, this is directly relevant. Mindfulness does not cure ADHD, but it builds a skill that compensates for one of its core deficits.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Zylowska et al. (2008) published the first RCT of Mindfulness-Based Cognitive Training (MBCT) adapted for ADHD adults, showing significant improvement in self-reported ADHD symptoms, anxiety, and depression.<br><span class="rich-cite">Zylowska L et al. J Atten Disord. 2008;11(6):737.</span></li>
  <li>A meta-analysis of 12 studies found medium effect sizes for mindfulness on inattention and small-to-medium effects on hyperactivity-impulsivity in adults with ADHD.<br><span class="rich-cite">Cairncross M &amp; Miller CJ. J Atten Disord. 2020;24(5):627.</span></li>
  <li>Recommended formats: MBCT (Mindfulness-Based Cognitive Therapy) or MBSR (Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction), delivered by a trained instructor over 8 weeks. Apps such as Headspace and Insight Timer can supplement but are not a substitute for structured training.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_nonpharm_dbt: `<div class="rich-h1">Non-Pharmacological Therapies</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Dialectical Behaviour Therapy (DBT) Skills</div>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Evidence: Moderate to strong, particularly for emotional dysregulation.</strong></p>
<p class="rich-p">DBT was originally developed for borderline personality disorder but its skills training component — distress tolerance, emotion regulation, interpersonal effectiveness, and mindfulness — maps very well onto the emotional dysregulation that is one of the most functionally impairing but least-discussed features of ADHD.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Hesslinger et al. (2002) adapted DBT specifically for adult ADHD and showed significant improvement in ADHD symptoms, self-esteem, and depression in a pilot RCT.<br><span class="rich-cite">Hesslinger B et al. Eur Arch Psychiatry Clin Neurosci. 2002;252(4):177.</span></li>
  <li>Particularly useful if emotional reactivity, impulsive outbursts, or relationship instability are prominent features.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_nonpharm_exercise: `<div class="rich-h1">Non-Pharmacological Therapies</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Exercise</div>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Evidence: Strong, particularly for acute attentional improvement and mood regulation.</strong></p>
<p class="rich-p">Aerobic exercise acutely increases dopamine and noradrenaline in the prefrontal cortex — the same systems that ADHD medication targets. The effect is shorter-lived than medication but clinically significant.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>A meta-analysis of 17 studies found acute aerobic exercise significantly improved executive function, attention, working memory, and inhibitory control in individuals with ADHD. Effect sizes were moderate to large.<br><span class="rich-cite">Mehren A et al. Neurosci Biobehav Rev. 2020;118:1.</span></li>
  <li>Recommended: 20-30 minutes of moderate-to-vigorous aerobic exercise (enough to raise heart rate significantly) in the morning, before or alongside medication. Cycling, running, and swimming all qualify. Consistency matters more than intensity.</li>
  <li>Exercise also improves sleep quality, which is commonly disrupted in ADHD and itself worsens executive function.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_nonpharm_ot: `<div class="rich-h1">Non-Pharmacological Therapies</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Occupational Therapy (OT)</div>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Evidence: Emerging, particularly strong for daily living skills and environmental modification.</strong></p>
<p class="rich-p">An OT with ADHD experience can conduct a functional capacity assessment and implement practical interventions: home and workspace organisation, routine-building, assistive technology, and time management systems. OT is particularly valuable for people who need hands-on, individualised support with daily living rather than insight-based therapy. May be fundable through NDIS.</p>`,

    s_sh_braindump: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<p class="rich-p">These are not generic productivity tips. Each one addresses a specific mechanism of ADHD — the interest-driven attention system, working memory deficits, difficulty initiating tasks, and the role of friction and reward in habit formation. Try one or two at a time rather than implementing everything at once.</p>

<div class="rich-h2">1. The Brain Dump + Priority Matrix</div>
<p class="rich-p">The ADHD brain cannot efficiently hold multiple open loops in working memory. When there are too many unresolved items floating around, the result is a persistent background anxiety and an inability to start any single thing. The solution is to get everything out of your head and onto a list — not a to-do list, a brain dump. Everything, regardless of size or urgency.</p>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>How to do it:</strong> Open your phone notes or a journal. Write down everything on your mind — taxes, a message you need to reply to, that you need to make your bed, an overdue assignment, a bill, a conversation you are avoiding, groceries, anything. Do not filter or organise while you are dumping. Then, once the list is complete, rate each item using the following system:</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>A — Urgent AND causes anxiety.</strong> Example: an email you have been avoiding, a payment overdue, a form that has a deadline. These are creating the most cognitive load.</li>
  <li><strong>B — Urgent but does NOT cause anxiety.</strong> Example: picking up a prescription, booking an appointment you actually want to go to. These need doing but are not emotionally charged.</li>
  <li><strong>C — Causes anxiety but is NOT urgent.</strong> Example: a difficult conversation you are dreading that has no fixed deadline. Real, but not time-critical today.</li>
  <li><strong>D — Neither urgent NOR anxiety-causing.</strong> Example: reorganising a drawer, watching a documentary. Fine, but do not let these crowd out A and B items.</li>
</ul>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Where to start:</strong> Look at all the A and B items. Find the one that is quickest and easiest to resolve — not the most important, the quickest. A message to a friend about plans tomorrow might be category A and takes 90 seconds. Send it now. Cross it off. Then find the next quickest resolvable item. The goal is not to work hardest on the hardest things — it is to progressively free up working memory and reduce anxiety load so that the harder things become more approachable. You will often find that after clearing five quick items, you have mental space and momentum to tackle something bigger.</p>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>When to do it:</strong> Whenever you feel overwhelmed, scattered, or paralysed by where to start. Also works well as a weekly reset on Sunday evening or Monday morning. Some people find a daily brain dump the single most useful ADHD management habit they have.</p>`,

    s_sh_phone: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Reducing Phone and Social Media Use</div>
<p class="rich-p">Smartphones are optimised to capture and hold attention — and for ADHD brains, which are already prone to distraction and seeking immediate stimulation, this is a particularly serious problem. The goal is not willpower. The goal is friction — making undesirable habits physically harder to do.</p>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Adding friction on iPhone:</strong></p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Hidden folders:</strong> Move Instagram, TikTok, and other high-dopamine apps into a folder within a folder on a back page of your home screen. You can still access them, but the extra steps break the automatic tap-and-open reflex. A surprising amount of mindless scrolling is prevented by this alone.</li>
  <li><strong>Screen Time limits (Settings &gt; Screen Time):</strong> Set daily time limits for specific apps. When the limit is reached, the app greyes out and requires a passcode to continue. Have someone else set the passcode if you do not trust yourself to override it.</li>
  <li><strong>Grayscale mode:</strong> Turn your screen to grayscale (Settings &gt; Accessibility &gt; Display &amp; Text Size &gt; Colour Filters). Colour is a key part of what makes apps visually compelling. Grayscale makes the phone less attractive and reduces impulsive use.</li>
  <li><strong>Notifications off for all non-essential apps:</strong> Every notification is an interruption that fragments attention. Turn off all badge, banner, and sound notifications except calls and calendar. Check messages on your schedule, not theirs.</li>
  <li><strong>Charge your phone outside the bedroom:</strong> Night-time scrolling disrupts sleep, which worsens ADHD the next day. An alarm clock costs $15 and removes the only reason most people keep a phone bedside.</li>
</ul>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>On Android:</strong> Digital Wellbeing (Settings &gt; Digital Wellbeing) provides app timers, focus mode (which locks selected apps for a set period), and Bedtime mode.</p>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Why friction works:</strong> Most problematic phone use is automatic and unconscious, not deliberate. The ADHD brain responds to availability — if the app is one tap away, the reflex fires. If it requires four steps, the reflex is often not strong enough to sustain. You are not fighting willpower; you are redesigning the environment.</p>`,

    s_sh_timeblock: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Time Blocking and Visual Timers</div>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD impairs time perception — time feels abstract and it is genuinely difficult to feel the passage of time or accurately predict how long things will take. "I have time" and "I am running out of time" can both feel the same until a deadline is imminent. The solution is to make time visible.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Time blocking:</strong> Allocate specific tasks to specific time slots in a calendar — not just a to-do list. A to-do list tells you what. A calendar tells you when. Time blocking converts intentions into commitments. Be realistic: ADHD tasks take longer than estimated. Add buffer time.</li>
  <li><strong>The Time Timer:</strong> A visual countdown timer (available as an app or physical device) shows time as a shrinking red disc. This makes the passage of time concrete rather than abstract. Particularly useful for tasks you tend to underestimate or avoid. Search "Time Timer" on the App Store.</li>
  <li><strong>The Pomodoro Technique:</strong> Work for 25 minutes, then take a mandatory 5-minute break. After four cycles, take a longer break. This creates structure, makes tasks feel finite, and exploits the fact that ADHD brains can often sustain focus for a defined short interval more reliably than open-ended sessions. Use a timer, not your phone clock.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_bodydouble: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Body Doubling</div>
<p class="rich-p">Body doubling is the practice of working in the presence of another person — physically or via video — without necessarily collaborating. Research and extensive self-report data from ADHD communities shows that many people with ADHD can initiate and sustain tasks dramatically better when someone else is simply present in the same space.</p>
<p class="rich-p">The mechanism is not fully understood but likely relates to social attention modulation and mild external accountability. Even a video call where both people are working silently on separate tasks produces the effect for many people.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Try working in a library, cafe, or co-working space rather than alone at home</li>
  <li>Arrange "accountability calls" with a friend where you each say what you are working on, then check back in 30-60 minutes</li>
  <li>Online body doubling communities: Focusmate (focusmate.com) matches you with a stranger for a 50-minute virtual co-working session — free for a limited number of sessions per week</li>
</ul>

<div class="rich-h2">5. "If-Then" Implementation Intentions</div>
<p class="rich-p">The ADHD brain struggles with prospective memory — remembering to do things at the right time. "Implementation intentions" are a specific technique from psychological research: instead of setting a general intention ("I will exercise more"), you specify a trigger: "When I finish my morning coffee, I will put on my shoes and go for a walk."</p>
<p class="rich-p">The research on this is substantial. Implementation intentions increase follow-through in the general population by 2-3 times. In people with executive dysfunction, the effect is even larger because the if-then structure offloads the initiation decision from working memory onto environmental cues.<br><span class="rich-cite">Gollwitzer PM &amp; Sheeran P. Adv Exp Soc Psychol. 2006;38:69.</span></p>
<p class="rich-p"><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>"When my alarm goes off at 7am, I will take my medication before I look at my phone."</li>
  <li>"When I sit down at my desk, I will open the document I need to work on before checking email."</li>
  <li>"When I feel the urge to check social media while working, I will write down what I was working on and come back to it."</li>
</ul>

<div class="rich-h2">6. Reducing Decision Fatigue</div>
<p class="rich-p">Every decision uses executive resources that ADHD brains have less of. The more decisions you make early in the day, the less capacity you have for the ones that matter. The solution is to systematically eliminate low-value decisions through routines.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Prepare tomorrow's clothes, bag, and anything needed before bed the night before</li>
  <li>Have a small rotation of default meals for weekday breakfasts and lunches — one fewer category of daily decisions</li>
  <li>Create a "launch pad" near the front door where keys, wallet, bag, and medication always live — searching for these things is a daily executive function tax</li>
  <li>Use recurring calendar events for regular tasks (gym, grocery shopping, calls) rather than deciding each week</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_reward: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Reward Pairing for Aversive Tasks</div>
<p class="rich-p">The ADHD brain is under-stimulated by low-interest tasks. The trick is not to force motivation — it is to pair the aversive task with something that adds stimulation without replacing the task.</p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>Listen to music, podcasts, or audiobooks only while doing routine household tasks (cleaning, cooking, folding). This makes the task feel different and makes the audio reward contingent on the activity.</li>
  <li>Work in a preferred environment — the coffee shop effect is real. A novel, mildly stimulating environment can sustain engagement longer than a familiar, quiet one for ADHD brains.</li>
  <li>Use a specific playlist only for focused work. Over time, the music becomes a cue that activates the "working" state.</li>
  <li>Set a small, concrete reward for completing a defined block of work — not "when I finish this project" (too remote) but "after I write this section, I will make a coffee." Concrete and proximate rewards activate the dopamine system more reliably than distant ones.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_ifthen: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">If-Then Planning</div>
<p class="rich-p">The ADHD brain struggles with initiating tasks — not because of laziness, but because the automatic link between "it is time to start" and actually starting is weaker. If-then planning (implementation intentions) builds that link explicitly.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">How to use it</div>
<p class="rich-p">Format: <strong>If [situation], then I will [action].</strong></p>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li>"If it is 9am and I sit at my desk, then I will open the document I need to work on first."</li>
  <li>"If I finish eating dinner, then I will put my medication out for tomorrow morning immediately."</li>
  <li>"If my phone buzzes while I am working, then I will place it face-down and return to what I was doing before checking it."</li>
</ul>
<p class="rich-p">The more specific the if-then, the more effective. Vague intentions ("I will try to start earlier") do not work for ADHD brains. Concrete, situation-specific triggers do. Write them down and place them somewhere visible.</p>`,

    s_sh_decisions: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Managing Decision Fatigue</div>
<p class="rich-p">Every decision — even trivial ones — draws on the same pool of executive function that ADHD already taxes. Reducing the number of decisions you have to make preserves mental energy for things that matter.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">Practical strategies</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Automate recurring decisions:</strong> Set a weekly meal structure, wear similar clothes, create default answers for common requests. "I don't schedule meetings before 10am" removes that negotiation every time.</li>
  <li><strong>Batch similar decisions:</strong> Rather than deciding what to buy when you go shopping, use a standing shopping list you update throughout the week.</li>
  <li><strong>Set decision rules in advance:</strong> "If I haven't used it in 12 months, I donate it" removes dozens of micro-decisions. Rules made in advance don't require executive function at the time.</li>
  <li><strong>Limit choices:</strong> Having fewer options is genuinely easier. Curate your wardrobe, your apps, your commitments.</li>
  <li><strong>Make hard decisions in the morning:</strong> Executive function is generally stronger earlier in the day. Schedule important decisions before fatigue compounds.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_bingeeating: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Binge Eating and ADHD</div>
<p class="rich-p">Binge eating is significantly more common in ADHD and is not simply about willpower or food. The ADHD brain seeks dopamine, and food — particularly highly palatable, calorie-dense food — provides a reliable and immediate dopamine hit. Impulsivity reduces the pause between urge and action. Inattention means meals are skipped or irregular, driving hunger that accelerates loss of control. Understanding this helps remove shame and directs effort toward what actually works.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">What helps</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Eat regularly:</strong> Skipping meals (especially when ADHD medication suppresses appetite at lunch) leads to significant hunger later, which makes eating regulation much harder. A small, scheduled lunch — even when not very hungry — reduces evening overconsumption.</li>
  <li><strong>Reduce friction for regular eating, increase friction for bingeing:</strong> Keep easy, adequate food accessible; make high-stimulation binge foods harder to reach (don't buy them, store them out of sight, require preparation).</li>
  <li><strong>Identify the emotional trigger:</strong> Binge urges often follow boredom, procrastination, frustration, or overwhelm in ADHD — not just physical hunger. Noticing "I am not hungry, I am avoiding something" is the first step to choosing a different response.</li>
  <li><strong>Address the dopamine need directly:</strong> If binge eating is serving as a dopamine source, other dopamine-generating activities (movement, music, a brief engaging task) can reduce the urge without the eating.</li>
  <li><strong>If binge eating is significantly impacting your life:</strong> This is worth raising with your psychiatrist. Medication changes and/or psychological support (particularly CBT-E or DBT) have good evidence.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_emotional: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Emotional Dysregulation</div>
<p class="rich-p">Emotional dysregulation is one of the most impairing and least discussed features of ADHD. Emotions arrive fast, feel intense, and are hard to modulate — not because of poor character, but because the prefrontal cortex circuits that regulate emotional responses are the same ones affected by ADHD. Frustration, rejection sensitivity, irritability, and sudden mood shifts are part of the condition.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">What helps</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Name it to tame it:</strong> Labelling an emotion — "I am feeling rejected" or "this is frustration, not a crisis" — activates the prefrontal cortex and reduces amygdala reactivity. It sounds simple and actually works.</li>
  <li><strong>Buy time before responding:</strong> The ADHD brain's fast emotional reaction is often followed by regret. Inserting a delay — leaving the room, saying "I need five minutes," putting down the phone — gives the cortex time to catch up. The decision to delay must be made in advance, not in the moment.</li>
  <li><strong>Physical regulation first:</strong> When emotionally dysregulated, physical activity (even a brisk 5-minute walk), cold water on the face, or controlled breathing reduces physiological arousal and improves the capacity to think clearly.</li>
  <li><strong>Rejection-sensitive dysphoria (RSD):</strong> If you experience sudden, intense emotional pain in response to perceived rejection or criticism — even mild — this is RSD, a common ADHD feature. Knowing it has a name and a mechanism helps. Discuss it with your psychiatrist; some medications help significantly.</li>
  <li><strong>DBT skills:</strong> Dialectical Behaviour Therapy was developed for emotion dysregulation and has strong evidence. A DBT therapist or self-help workbook can provide structured tools.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_kids: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Parenting Difficulties with ADHD</div>
<p class="rich-p">Parenting is hard. Parenting with ADHD is harder — and if you have a child who also has ADHD, the demands can be overwhelming. ADHD affects the very skills parenting requires most: consistency, patience, sustained attention, emotional regulation, and planning ahead. This is not a character failure; it is a brain-based challenge.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">What helps</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Reduce cognitive load:</strong> Simplify routines to the minimum viable version. Visual schedules on the wall that both you and your child can follow reduce the number of verbal reminders and arguments.</li>
  <li><strong>Short, specific instructions:</strong> "Shoes on, bag by the door" rather than a chain of instructions. One step at a time works better for ADHD brains — yours and theirs.</li>
  <li><strong>Repair quickly:</strong> ADHD parents often lose patience and say things they regret. A quick, genuine repair — "I got angry and that wasn't fair, I'm sorry" — matters more to long-term relationship quality than having never lost patience.</li>
  <li><strong>Your own medication:</strong> If you are on ADHD medication, taking it consistently (including weekends) makes a measurable difference to parenting patience and follow-through.</li>
  <li><strong>Structure for yourself:</strong> Use the same planning tools for parenting tasks that you use for work tasks — calendars, reminders, checklists. Externalise what you can't hold in working memory.</li>
  <li><strong>Get support:</strong> Parent management training adapted for ADHD families (such as the Triple P or 1-2-3 Magic programmes) has good evidence. If you are struggling significantly, your psychiatrist can refer you.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_partner: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Relationships and ADHD</div>
<p class="rich-p">ADHD affects relationships in predictable, often painful ways: forgetfulness is misread as not caring, emotional dysregulation creates escalating conflicts, hyperfocus on a new relationship gives way to inattention once novelty fades, and the non-ADHD partner often becomes the default organiser, which breeds resentment over time.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">What helps</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Externalise memory:</strong> Shared digital calendars, to-do apps, and household management lists reduce the reliance on the ADHD brain's unreliable internal organisation — and make it visible to your partner that things are being tracked.</li>
  <li><strong>Have a consistent check-in:</strong> A brief weekly conversation — "what's on this week, what do we each need from the other" — prevents the accumulation of unvoiced frustrations and missed commitments.</li>
  <li><strong>Separate intent from impact:</strong> Forgetting your partner's important appointment is not the same as not caring about them. Acknowledging the impact without defensiveness, and problem-solving together (what system would help?), is more productive than the "I didn't mean to" / "but you always" loop.</li>
  <li><strong>Discuss the diagnosis together:</strong> If your partner understands ADHD as a brain-based condition rather than selfishness or immaturity, it changes the frame. Many couples find couples therapy — particularly with a therapist familiar with ADHD — helpful.</li>
  <li><strong>The ADHD partner's responsibility:</strong> Having ADHD explains your difficulties; it does not remove the responsibility to work on them. Partners need to see consistent effort, even when the effort looks different from neurotypical organisation.</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_commsadult: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Communicating Effectively with an Adult Who Has ADHD</div>
<p class="rich-p">If you are reading this because someone in your life has ADHD — or because you want to share it with them — here are practical communication approaches that work with ADHD brains rather than against them.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">What works</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>One thing at a time:</strong> A list of instructions — "can you pick up the kids, remember to call the plumber, and don't forget dinner is at 7" — will likely result in one item being remembered. Prioritise and communicate one request per conversation.</li>
  <li><strong>Get attention first:</strong> Say their name and wait for eye contact before giving important information. Starting to speak while they are absorbed in something else means the message is not received.</li>
  <li><strong>Write it down:</strong> Text a request after mentioning it verbally. This is not a slight; it is how ADHD working memory actually works.</li>
  <li><strong>Short, direct, specific:</strong> "The appointment is Friday at 2pm, I've sent you a calendar invite" works. "I mentioned it last week and really hope you haven't forgotten again" doesn't.</li>
  <li><strong>Timing matters:</strong> Raising an important topic when they are in the middle of a task, on the phone, or hyperfocused means it will not be properly heard. Ask "is now a good time?" for important conversations.</li>
  <li><strong>Assume distraction, not disrespect:</strong> If something was forgotten or missed, a curious "did you get a chance to..." lands very differently to an accusatory "you never remember anything I ask."</li>
</ul>`,

    s_sh_commschild: `<div class="rich-h1">Self-Help Techniques</div>
<div class="rich-h2">Talking With a Child Who Has ADHD</div>
<p class="rich-p">Children with ADHD hear far more correction, criticism, and redirection than their peers — studies suggest up to 20,000 more negative interactions by age 10. The goal is to interrupt that pattern without removing necessary structure.</p>
<div class="rich-h3">What works</div>
<ul class="rich-ul">
  <li><strong>Catch them being good:</strong> Describe the positive behaviour specifically when you see it — "I noticed you put your bag away without being asked, that's great." Vague praise ("good job") is less effective than named praise.</li>
  <li><strong>Instructions: short, specific, one at a time:</strong> "Shoes on" rather than "get ready." "Sit at the table" rather than "stop running around and come and eat your dinner." Wait for compliance before giving the next instruction.</li>
  <li><strong>Get physical proximity and eye contact first:</strong> Calling from another room rarely works. Move close, make eye contact (without demanding it aggressively), then speak.</li>
  <li><strong>Explain the why, briefly:</strong> Children with ADHD respond better to reasons than to authority alone — "we need to leave now because the appointment is at 3 and we need to park" is more effective than "because I said so."</li>
  <li><strong>Use visual supports:</strong> Morning routine charts, step-by-step checklists with pictures, and visible timers reduce the number of verbal prompts needed and give the child autonomy.</li>
  <li><strong>Choose your battles:</strong> If everything is a battle, the currency of correction is devalued. Reserve firm limits for safety and non-negotiables; let minor things go.</li>
  <li><strong>Avoid public correction where possible:</strong> ADHD children are often already hyperaware of being different. Quiet correction, away from peers, is more effective and less damaging to self-esteem.</li>
</ul>`,

